programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. After seven years working in Germany, Sarah Brodie-Fraser and her English-born husband Alistair have decided to relocate to Sarah's home town of Toowoomba in Queensland. Their plan is to build a classic farmhouse that could be plucked from rural England and dropped onto their one-acre sloping block. From the steeply pitched tiled roof and traditional European interiors to the wood block herringbone flooring, they are committed to making everything as authentic as possible, with touches of fantasy including a traditional library with mezzanine wrap-around gallery and spiral staircase. It's all on a scale rarely seen in domestic architecture: 900 square metres on a precipitous site that needs 100 deeply set piers buried under 50 truckloads of concrete just to get the plot horizontal, plus enormous retaining walls cut from the local sandstone quarry. It's a massive venture that requires more than part-time interest, and brave Alistair is up for the job, throwing in his full-time work to self-manage the project. But as the house fills out, the demands and pressure on Alistair intensify. It's a level of work that's bound to have repercussions for the build... and for Alistair himself

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. When Jason Bretell and Jennifer Pancari first set eyes on a dilapidated bluestone cottage in the Melbourne bayside suburb of Williamstown, it was love at first sight. The 150-year-old derelict structure was frozen in time, with decaying tools and other remnants among the ruins: bits and pieces Jason and Jen hope to salvage as they bring the place back to life. Their plan is to restore the tiny four-roomed cottage and add a two-storey contemporary townhouse on the back: a modern, edgy, industrial-style structure that contrasts sharply with the heritage bluestone frontage. It sounds romantic, but the reality is far from that. Storm water damage means the whole front wall has to be deconstructed and rebuilt, and there's more grief when the original roof won't match up with its new counterpart. Jason and Jen are hands-on when it comes to selecting materials, they have a wedding planned mid-build, and with no architect and tight finances, Jen takes on designing the kitchen and bathroom, as well as starting a new job. The couple are spreading themselves thin in an effort to see their project through. Can they find the balance between the old and the new to salvage this little piece of history?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they try to design and construct the home of their dreams. After seven years working in Germany, Sarah Brodie-Fraser and her English-born husband Alistair have decided to relocate to Sarah's home town of Toowoomba in Queensland. Their plan is to build a classic farmhouse that could be plucked from rural England and dropped onto their one-acre sloping block. From the steeply pitched tiled roof and traditional European interiors to the wood block herringbone flooring, they are committed to making everything as authentic as possible, with touches of fantasy including a traditional library with mezzanine wrap-around gallery and spiral staircase. It's all on a scale rarely seen in domestic architecture: 900 square metres on a precipitous site that needs 100 deeply set piers buried under 50 truckloads of concrete just to get the plot horizontal, plus enormous retaining walls cut from the local sandstone quarry. It's a massive venture that requires more than part-time interest, and brave Alistair is up for the job, throwing in his full-time work to self-manage the project. But as the house fills out, the demands and pressure on Alistair intensify. It's a level of work that's bound to have repercussions for the build... and for Alistair himself

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. When Jason Bretell and Jennifer Pancari first set eyes on a dilapidated bluestone cottage in the Melbourne bayside suburb of Williamstown, it was love at first sight. The 150-year-old derelict structure was frozen in time, with decaying tools and other remnants among the ruins: bits and pieces Jason and Jen hope to salvage as they bring the place back to life. Their plan is to restore the tiny four-roomed cottage and add a two-storey contemporary townhouse on the back: a modern, edgy, industrial-style structure that contrasts sharply with the heritage bluestone frontage. It sounds romantic, but the reality is far from that. Storm water damage means the whole front wall has to be deconstructed and rebuilt, and there's more grief when the original roof won't match up with its new counterpart. Jason and Jen are hands-on when it comes to selecting materials, they have a wedding planned mid-build, and with no architect and tight finances, Jen takes on designing the kitchen and bathroom, as well as starting a new job. The couple are spreading themselves thin in an effort to see their project through. Can they find the balance between the old and the new to salvage this little piece of history?(n)
